definition: "Fibrinogen is a soluble plasma glycoprotein produced by the liver that is the precursor to fibrin — the insoluble protein that forms the structural scaffold of blood clots. When a blood vessel is injured, thrombin cleaves fibrinogen into fibrin monomers that polymerize into a mesh that traps red blood cells and platelets to form a clot. Fibrinogen is also an acute phase reactant: its production increases substantially in response to inflammation, infection, and tissue injury — making it simultaneously a clotting factor and an inflammatory marker."
